{"term":"2009","caseName":"South Carolina v. North Carolina","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2009/138-orig","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 13, 2009","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts4/oral_argument_audio/21388","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear argument this afternoon in Case 138 in our original docket, South Carolina v. North Carolina.","start":0,"stop":7.667,"duration":7.67},{"text":"Mr. Frederick.","start":7.667,"stop":8.572,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: South Carolina seeks an equitable apportionment with North Carolina of the Catawba River.","start":8.572,"stop":18.18,"duration":9.61},{"text":"Both States act as parens patriae on behalf of all users of the river within their boundaries.","start":18.18,"stop":25.674,"duration":7.49},{"text":"For three reasons, this Court should not adopt the Special Master's recommendation that Charlotte, Duke, and the Catawba River Water Supply Project be permitted to intervene as parties in this original action: First, the report articulates the wrong legal test for intervention.","start":25.674,"stop":44.888,"duration":19.21},{"text":"Second, under the New Jersey v. New York standard, none of the three entities should be permitted to intervene.","start":44.888,"stop":52.196,"duration":7.31},{"text":"And, third, the report's approach to intervention involves this Court in deciding intramural disputes between and among water users in one State.","start":52.196,"stop":64.392,"duration":12.2},{"text":"With respect to the first point, the Special Master applied the wrong factors, we would submit, in deciding whether or not a party or an intervenor should be allowed to intervene as a party.","start":64.392,"stop":76.844,"duration":12.45},{"text":"The Special Master sought to distill from this Court's cases three principles that we would submit are not the appropriate principles in deciding an intervenor's status.","start":76.844,"stop":87.618,"duration":10.77},{"text":"First, the report overemphasizes the, quote, \"direct stake\", although the master found that the equitable apportionment had no specific impact on individual users of the water.","start":87.618,"stop":101.037,"duration":13.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought your friends agreed that the New Jersey v. New York standard applied?","start":101.037,"stop":105.22,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, part of what you will be deciding in this case is the appropriate standard for intervention, and the Special Master, we respectfully submit, did not apply the New Jersey v. New York factors.","start":105.22,"stop":118.152,"duration":12.93},{"text":"Instead, the report distilled from other cases, not the New Jersey v. New York case, the principles that she thought should apply to govern an intervenor's status, and those three principles, we would submit, are incorrect.","start":118.152,"stop":132.334,"duration":14.18},{"text":"Under the New Jersey v. New York standard, the master did not make findings that would be appropriate to determine the intervenor status here as appropriate parties.","start":132.334,"stop":144,"duration":11.67},{"text":"There was no finding of inadequate representation by either State to support any of the intervenor's request to participate as parties.","start":144,"stop":152.998,"duration":9},{"text":"There was no finding of a compelling interest in the sense that it was truly compelling.","start":152.998,"stop":158.464,"duration":5.47},{"text":"It's hard to argue in cases in -- where there is no case from this Court in the equitable apportionment area that three intervenors would have met the compelling interest standard here.","start":158.464,"stop":171.286,"duration":12.82},{"text":"And, finally, the New York-New Jersey standard talks about having interests that are apart from other interests.","start":171.286,"stop":180.52,"duration":9.23},{"text":"But both Charlotte and the Catawba River Water Supply Project are simply acting on behalf of all users of North Carolina water.","start":180.52,"stop":189.095,"duration":8.57},{"text":"They simply happen to be the largest ones.","start":189.095,"stop":191.669,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Frederick, we -- we had a case involving, what, a tax on -- on oil companies, in which it was a State against State case, but we allowed the oil companies who would pay the tax to intervene.","start":191.669,"stop":211.958,"duration":20.29},{"text":"Now, why is that any different from this case?","start":211.958,"stop":215.144,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"First, the interests were different.","start":215.144,"stop":218.143,"duration":3},{"text":"They were not an equitable apportionment where the water--","start":218.143,"stop":220.221,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why does that make any difference?","start":220.221,"stop":222.191,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--This Court has said for 200 years that water is a unique resource within the sovereign control of States.","start":222.191,"stop":227.813,"duration":5.62},{"text":"In the Maryland case, the Court permitted intervention in a situation in which Louisiana had sued the pipeline companies in Louisiana State court for a declaratory judgment that its tax was constitutional.","start":227.813,"stop":243.009,"duration":15.2},{"text":"There was also a pending FERC action in Federal court in Louisiana raising the same issue, so when Maryland and eight other States who were not parens patriae of the various pipeline companies who sought to intervene filed the original action, I think the Court appropriately considered that interests of judicial efficiency called for handling the Commerce Clause challenge in the original action in this case.","start":243.009,"stop":269.374,"duration":26.37},{"text":"And finally, the Court only devoted two sentences of its opinion and didn't cite the New Jersey v. -- New York v. New Jersey case in acting on the intervention.","start":269.374,"stop":280.776,"duration":11.4}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, well, these -- these are rules that we are making up ourselves, right, as to when we are going to allow intervention or not?","start":280.776,"stop":287.413,"duration":6.64},{"text":"Do -- is there any case -- I think there isn't, but tell me if I'm wrong -- is there any case in which we have rejected intervention that has been recommended by the Special Master?","start":287.413,"stop":300.719,"duration":13.31}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think I can recall a case in that factual scenario, but I can point you to Kentucky v. Indiana in 1930, in which this Court rejected Kentucky's attempt to join individual Indiana citizens as parties in an original action over Indiana's alleged breach of a contract to build an interstate bridge.","start":300.719,"stop":322.197,"duration":21.48},{"text":"And the reason--","start":322.197,"stop":322.914,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand your basic argument that each State should represent its own constituents.","start":322.914,"stop":328.194,"duration":5.28},{"text":"But isn't the Catawba River Water Supply Project in a different category?","start":328.194,"stop":334.379,"duration":6.19},{"text":"Because it straddles both States, and I think it can reasonably fear that it would be treated as a stepchild by both States.","start":334.379,"stop":341.703,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, in fact, Mr. Chief Justice, I would submit they have the weakest claim to intervention in this case.","start":341.703,"stop":347.263,"duration":5.56},{"text":"Their argument, fundamentally, is that Union County, North Carolina, which is the North Carolina part of the joint venture with the Lancaster Water District, should be permitted to have water purchased from the South Carolina side of the boundary.","start":347.263,"stop":362.194,"duration":14.93},{"text":"So what's happening with that water project is the water is sucked out on the South Carolina side and piped north for Union County's consumption under a Union County permit with the State of North Carolina.","start":362.194,"stop":375.219,"duration":13.02},{"text":"Union County, therefore, is acting as any other user of water, along with Charlotte and all other users of water in North Carolina.","start":375.219,"stop":384.293,"duration":9.07},{"text":"The Catawba Project is not here to intervene to protect its interests on the South Carolina side of the boundary.","start":384.293,"stop":390.371,"duration":6.08},{"text":"Those are adequately protected, we submit, by the attorney general acting on behalf of the State.","start":390.371,"stop":396.209,"duration":5.84},{"text":"So in effect the Union County, North Carolina, claim here of 5 million gallons of water per day which they are seeking to protect through their intervention is no different than the other interests of North Carolina water users that they are seeking to protect--","start":396.209,"stop":411.504,"duration":15.3}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except that these -- these three entities are the principal entities that are guilty of interbasin transfers, which is essentially what the -- what the dispute is about.","start":411.504,"stop":430.01,"duration":18.51}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--The dispute is about the transfer of water and consumption of water in toto.","start":430.01,"stop":436.132,"duration":6.12},{"text":"The Court--","start":436.132,"stop":437.1,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but the focus -- the focus of the complaint is upon interbasin transfers, isn't it?","start":437.1,"stop":441.583,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--The focus of the complaint highlights interbasin transfers to the extent that they are a large quantifiable amount of water being taken out of the Catawba River, that we submit should not be counted on--","start":441.583,"stop":454.655,"duration":13.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":454.655,"stop":455.627,"duration":0.97},{"text":"And these three entities account for a very large proportion of those interbasin transfers.","start":455.627,"stop":461.156,"duration":5.53},{"text":"Isn't it the case that any -- any decision by -- by this Court on -- on this question will necessarily impact directly these three entities?","start":461.156,"stop":473.337,"duration":12.18}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":473.337,"stop":473.868,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why not?","start":473.868,"stop":474.835,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"Because in an equitable apportionment case, this Court decides which share of the water is allocable to each State.","start":474.835,"stop":483.457,"duration":8.62},{"text":"It is a question of State law how each State shall determine the intrastate allocations of the water.","start":483.457,"stop":490.203,"duration":6.75},{"text":"So--","start":490.203,"stop":490.686,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, but I'm talking about the real world.","start":490.686,"stop":492.781,"duration":2.1},{"text":"If -- if indeed North Carolina has to cut back, and if indeed the opinion of this Court says that it's taking too much because of interbasin transfers, as a practical matter these three entities are going to be out of luck.","start":492.781,"stop":507.416,"duration":14.63}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--We take the real world, Your Honor, as this Court's cases direct us, and those cases tell us that in situations where the Court is deciding an equitable apportionment between two States -- water, of course, is fungible.","start":507.416,"stop":522.05,"duration":14.63},{"text":"It's a series of molecules that do not accord property rights in any one entity or user.","start":522.05,"stop":529.58,"duration":7.53},{"text":"They all divine from the State itself.","start":529.58,"stop":532.033,"duration":2.45},{"text":"So if North Carolina, in its exercise of parens patriae responsibility, determines that Charlotte should have a larger share than what it currently has, that's a decision for Charlotte -- for North Carolina as a political entity to decide among its users.","start":532.033,"stop":546.652,"duration":14.62},{"text":"It does not necessarily implicate this Court's action in an equitable apportionment to say that what the Court will ultimately decide is what Charlotte's share is.","start":546.652,"stop":558.207,"duration":11.55},{"text":"That is not what we are seeking, and that's not what an injunction from this Court equitably apportioning the Catawba River would necessarily decide.","start":558.207,"stop":566.064,"duration":7.86}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you--","start":566.064,"stop":566.329,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Frederick, if this were an ordinary civil case, we would be guided by the rule on permissive intervention, and appellate courts in dealing with that rule give a healthy measure of respect to the trial judge's determination.","start":566.329,"stop":590.163,"duration":23.83},{"text":"So even though the civil rules are not binding in original jurisdiction cases, isn't that a sound approach that we should adopt?","start":590.163,"stop":600.676,"duration":10.51},{"text":"Just as a court of appeals would defer to a district judge's decision, so we should give a healthy measure of deference to the Special Master's evaluation that this will be useful.","start":600.676,"stop":613.701,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"No, for several reasons, Justice Ginsburg.","start":613.701,"stop":615.623,"duration":1.92},{"text":"First, in any appellate review Situation, this Court would review de novo the legal test that would be applied.","start":615.623,"stop":622.697,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Our initial submission is the master applied and articulated the wrong legal test.","start":622.697,"stop":627.353,"duration":4.66},{"text":"So you would first need to determine, we would submit, what is the correct legal test for submission.","start":627.353,"stop":632.6,"duration":5.25},{"text":"That is a de novo review standard.","start":632.6,"stop":634.52,"duration":1.92},{"text":"But secondly, the Court has said in numerous original cases it does not apply deference, although it gives appropriate respect to special masters, and so there would be no basis for applying a deference standard to a special master ruling on a question of law that fundamentally is about what this Court's original jurisdiction under Article III is supposed to be about.","start":634.52,"stop":658.432,"duration":23.91}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--But, in fact, we've never rejected a special master's desire to -- to have intervenors in the case.","start":658.432,"stop":665.884,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, virtually every case, Justice Scalia--","start":665.884,"stop":667.744,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And that oil case that I mentioned.","start":667.744,"stop":668.695,"duration":0.95},{"text":"I forget the name of it.","start":668.695,"stop":669.678,"duration":0.98},{"text":"The tax--","start":669.678,"stop":670.177,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--Maryland v. Louisiana.","start":670.177,"stop":671.71,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":671.71,"stop":672.037,"duration":0.33},{"text":"What had the Special Master recommended in that case?","start":672.037,"stop":673.897,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"There was actually no special master recommendation in that case.","start":673.897,"stop":676.692,"duration":2.79},{"text":"The Court decided it on its motion directly to this Court.","start":676.692,"stop":681.423,"duration":4.73},{"text":"Virtually all of the cases that we cited in the blue brief highlight the fact that special masters routinely reject motions to intervene.","start":681.423,"stop":690.307,"duration":8.88},{"text":"It is the rare situation in which a special master would allow intervention.","start":690.307,"stop":695.212,"duration":4.9},{"text":"And the only example that the other side can come up with is the Nebraska v. Wyoming case, in which finally Basin Electric, after 10 years of participating in the original action as an amicus, was allowed to intervene because the Special Master viewed there to be tension between the State of Nebraska's interest and that that Basin Electric was seeking to vindicate.","start":695.212,"stop":718.656,"duration":23.44},{"text":"You--","start":718.656,"stop":719.124,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Frederick, can we go back a little?","start":719.124,"stop":721.249,"duration":2.13},{"text":"I think you just said there was no special master's recommendation in Maryland v. Louisiana, but I'm looking at page 745.","start":721.249,"stop":731.337,"duration":10.09},{"text":"In the footnote 21, it said:","start":731.337,"stop":735.011,"duration":3.67},{"text":"\"The master recommended that we grant the motion of 17 pipeline companies to intervene as plaintiffs. \"","start":735.011,"stop":743.41,"duration":8.4},{"text":"And then it says:","start":743.41,"stop":746.112,"duration":2.7},{"text":"\"It is not unusual to permit intervention of private parties in original actions. \"","start":746.112,"stop":753.501,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--And the case that it cited is Oklahoma v. Texas, which is a very unusual case from this Court's docket in the 1920s.","start":753.501,"stop":763.511,"duration":10.01},{"text":"What the Court decided in 1932, Justice Ginsburg, in the Wyoming and Colorado case was that in situations involving interstate allocations of water, the claimants or users of a State are deemed to be represented by the State.","start":763.511,"stop":780.896,"duration":17.38},{"text":"The case on which the Court relied in the Maryland case was back into an old era in which it was unclear whether States acting as parens patriae had the responsibility to act on behalf of all claimants or users of water.","start":780.896,"stop":797.874,"duration":16.98},{"text":"The Maryland case, as I said before, did not analyze the New Jersey v. New York factors, and I would submit that in light of the other circumstances of the case, the fact that it was a Commerce Clause challenge involving Federal, State, and private companies, in which there was multiple litigation pending in various forums, it was an exercise of the Court's decision to efficiently decide the Commerce Clause challenge to allow those pipeline companies in, where some of those pipeline companies were not represented by States that were parties in the case.","start":797.874,"stop":835.668,"duration":37.79}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I guess I haven't heard yet an answer to Justice Ginsburg's first question about whether there was a recommendation from the Special Master or not.","start":835.668,"stop":843.151,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I will -- I obviously forgot about footnote 21 of the Court's opinion in Maryland v. Louisiana, Justice Ginsburg.","start":843.151,"stop":850.428,"duration":7.28},{"text":"But I think--","start":850.428,"stop":851.727,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, I don't know that you've actually addressed the operative question of what amount of discretion, if any, are we going to give to special masters to determine when they require the presence of a party to do equity, which is what I read the Special Master to be suggesting.","start":851.727,"stop":872.811,"duration":21.08},{"text":"These are the three biggest users of water, at least one of them straddles both States, another has a potential license.","start":872.811,"stop":883.901,"duration":11.09},{"text":"And so that each of them has a different situation than a normal water user.","start":883.901,"stop":891.63,"duration":7.73},{"text":"So, you're -- all you're begging is the question of whether we just say you can't.","start":891.63,"stop":898.63,"duration":7},{"text":"But why is the \"you can't\" compelled, either by our case law or by any original jurisdiction principle?","start":898.63,"stop":906.936,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, let's start with the original jurisdiction principle.","start":906.936,"stop":910.156,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Those are actions that are brought invoking this Court's original jurisdiction, which this Court could sit without a special master and would decide the matter as it sits as a court of nine.","start":910.156,"stop":920.01,"duration":9.85},{"text":"The fact that it appoints a special master to assist and facilitate that effort does not imbue the actions of that person delegated that responsibility with something akin to the deference given to district judges in making various fact findings.","start":920.01,"stop":937.894,"duration":17.88},{"text":"Secondly, on a question of law, as intervention fundamentally is -- and ultimately we are talking about the scope and contours of this Court's exercise of original jurisdiction -- what the Court has said is that there are two interests that are ultimately being protected: One is the dignity interest of the State acting in its sovereign capacity on a subject, water, that quintessentially is sovereign; and it is doing so for judicial efficiency purposes, because it allows the Court to expect each State to represent adequately all of the users of water in that State.","start":937.894,"stop":976.175,"duration":38.28},{"text":"So, for those reasons, we think that a special master recommendation ought to be reviewed with the same level of scrutiny that all other aspects of a special master's--","start":976.175,"stop":984.672,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we've -- we've allowed private parties to be impleaded by the States.","start":984.672,"stop":988.887,"duration":4.21},{"text":"We have allowed one State to sue another State and a private party.","start":988.887,"stop":992.763,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--Not in an equitable apportionment.","start":992.763,"stop":994.854,"duration":2.09},{"text":"And -- and I think the -- the scope of the relief is important.","start":994.854,"stop":997.899,"duration":3.04},{"text":"And that is because the State seeking the relief is assuming the risk that the relief that it wants to get from that State is an inadequate form of relief.","start":997.899,"stop":1008.537,"duration":10.64},{"text":"Here the form of relief South Carolina seeks goes only against North Carolina.","start":1008.537,"stop":1014.332,"duration":5.79},{"text":"We cannot get an equitable apportionment with Charlotte or the Catawba Project.","start":1014.332,"stop":1018.064,"duration":3.73},{"text":"We can only get it from North Carolina.","start":1018.064,"stop":1020.907,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't--","start":1020.907,"stop":1021.266,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I see your light's on, but can we take this case on the assumption that nothing that you obtain in the way of relief will affect Duke Power under the comprehensive relicensing agreement?","start":1021.266,"stop":1034.589,"duration":13.32}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes--","start":1034.589,"stop":1035.416,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't we have to take the case on the assumption that their rights under that agreement might be affected?","start":1035.416,"stop":1041.18,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--They might be affected, but only in an ancillary way.","start":1041.18,"stop":1046.491,"duration":5.31},{"text":"It is an -- part of an application to the FERC.","start":1046.491,"stop":1049.739,"duration":3.25},{"text":"The FERC here is saying it does not affect it because the license itself will not dictate minimum--","start":1049.739,"stop":1056.174,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But are you saying you are not seeking a result that's inconsistent in any way with that agreement?","start":1056.174,"stop":1060.705,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--Neither the agreement -- and this is at page 51 to 52 of our brief, citing 39 of the CRA -- says it doesn't affect water rights.","start":1060.705,"stop":1069.731,"duration":9.03},{"text":"The final environmental impact statement from FERC says it doesn't affect apportionment interstate issues.","start":1069.731,"stop":1076.01,"duration":6.28},{"text":"Both FERC and the CRA itself disclaim any impact on the equitable apportionment action pending here.","start":1076.01,"stop":1083.817,"duration":7.81},{"text":"If I could save the balance of my time.","start":1083.817,"stop":1085.49,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Frederick.","start":1085.49,"stop":1086.613,"duration":1.12},{"text":"Mr. Miller.","start":1086.613,"stop":1093.425,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: In order to intervene in an original action in this Court, a citizen of a State that is a party to the action must show a compelling interest, separate from that of other citizens, that is not properly represented by the State.","start":1093.425,"stop":1108.652,"duration":15.23},{"text":"In an equitable apportionment action, the interest that is at stake is not a private property interest in water.","start":1108.652,"stop":1114.131,"duration":5.48},{"text":"Rather, it is the sovereign interest of a State in a particular share of the waters of an interstate river.","start":1114.131,"stop":1119.988,"duration":5.86},{"text":"For that reason, a private interest in water is not an appropriate basis for intervention in such a proceeding.","start":1119.988,"stop":1126.068,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It depends on, I suppose, on what you mean by","start":1126.068,"stop":1129.394,"duration":3.33},{"text":"\"is not properly represented by the State. \"","start":1129.394,"stop":1131.937,"duration":2.54},{"text":"If you think the State does not have a sufficient interest to defend that -- that particular right vigorously, might that not be -- might not that qualify?","start":1131.937,"stop":1146.606,"duration":14.67}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that the interest that the private party has is a State law property interest in water, and that's an interest that simply isn't at stake in an equitable apportionment action.","start":1146.606,"stop":1159.24,"duration":12.63},{"text":"The only thing that this Court is deciding is what share of the river does each State get.","start":1159.24,"stop":1165.706,"duration":6.47},{"text":"The Court in an equitable apportionment action does not decide the purely intrastate question of how will that share be allocated.","start":1165.706,"stop":1173.903,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you could say that realistically when you are talking about an individual water user, a small potatoes water user, a normal resident of Charlotte perhaps.","start":1173.903,"stop":1184.541,"duration":10.64},{"text":"But when you are talking about the biggest entities that are going to be affected by the apportionment, it really doesn't ring true to me.","start":1184.541,"stop":1192.866,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- I mean, in New Jersey v. New York, Philadelphia, which sought to intervene in that case, constituted a majority of the water users within the State of Philadelphia.","start":1192.866,"stop":1204.14,"duration":11.27}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the special master think Philadelphia should have been let in?","start":1204.14,"stop":1207.891,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't recall what the special master--","start":1207.891,"stop":1210.203,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"The answer is no.","start":1210.203,"stop":1211.295,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--said in that case.","start":1211.295,"stop":1213.342,"duration":2.05},{"text":"But this Court has held in, for example, Colorado v. New Mexico, that even on purely factual questions, the special master is -- who makes recommendations, and those recommendations are reviewed by this Court de novo.","start":1213.342,"stop":1226.804,"duration":13.46},{"text":"The Court is not sitting in an appellate capacity.","start":1226.804,"stop":1230.115,"duration":3.31},{"text":"This is a case within its original jurisdiction, and this Court has an independent responsibility to make a determination, even on factual questions and a fortiori on questions of intervention.","start":1230.115,"stop":1240.952,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but we haven't -- we haven't been sitting there trying to figure out what would facilitate the proceeding.","start":1240.952,"stop":1247.888,"duration":6.94},{"text":"Much of the discovery in the case has already focused on these three entities, hasn't it?","start":1247.888,"stop":1255.368,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1255.368,"stop":1256.994,"duration":1.63},{"text":"And to the extent--","start":1256.994,"stop":1257.899,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So to say that they are just -- you know, they are just Joe Dokes is -- is really very unrealistic.","start":1257.899,"stop":1263.756,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, to the -- I mean, to the extent that they have valuable information to provide, third-party discovery can take account of that, as can amicus participation.","start":1263.756,"stop":1272.3,"duration":8.54},{"text":"It would be entirely appropriate for parties that have information or a special perspective on the case to present an amicus submission to the Special Master or to this Court.","start":1272.3,"stop":1283.452,"duration":11.15},{"text":"And it's -- but that -- that's not a basis for allowing them to become full parties through intervention.","start":1283.452,"stop":1291.321,"duration":7.87},{"text":"And then, to the extent that there's a concern about the management of this case, I think it's important to keep in mind that the rule recommended by the Special Master and the rule that the would-be intervenors are urging this Court to adopt would, of course, apply not just in this litigation, but in every equitable apportionment action.","start":1291.321,"stop":1310.597,"duration":19.28},{"text":"And not only does it make the litigation of those actions much more difficult to have additional non-State parties in, but it makes it much more difficult for those cases to be settled.","start":1310.597,"stop":1321.968,"duration":11.37}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if that -- if and when that is the case, the Special Master will not want them to come in, as the vast majority of special masters have not wanted them to come in, in the past.","start":1321.968,"stop":1333.663,"duration":11.69},{"text":"I don't think that's going to change.","start":1333.663,"stop":1335.227,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I guess what I would say is that I don't think that, either in the recommendation of the Special Master in this case or in the submissions of the -- the would-be intervenors, that there's really any logical limiting principle that would not allow, as a matter of routine, large water users to come in to equitable apportionment actions.","start":1335.227,"stop":1360.796,"duration":25.57},{"text":"And that's inappropriate for the more fundamental reason that these original actions in this Court are not ordinary cases.","start":1360.796,"stop":1370.307,"duration":9.51},{"text":"This Court has said that sitting in judgment between two sovereigns is one of the most grave -- grave and delicate responsibilities the Court has, and it's a sparingly exercised jurisdiction reserved for the most serious of issues, issues of such importance that, if the States were independent countries, would be resolved through treaties or--","start":1370.307,"stop":1391.266,"duration":20.96}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But not reserved exclusively to State -- to suits between a State and another State.","start":1391.266,"stop":1396.219,"duration":4.95},{"text":"We've allowed it to cover suits between a State and another State and private citizens of the other State.","start":1396.219,"stop":1402.326,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1402.326,"stop":1403.449,"duration":1.12},{"text":"And when a State brings such an action or seeks to bring such an action, it can't simply file a complaint as of right.","start":1403.449,"stop":1409.633,"duration":6.18},{"text":"It has to seek this Court's permission to file the complaint.","start":1409.633,"stop":1414.103,"duration":4.47},{"text":"And this Court can review the complaint at that time and look at who the parties are and figure out whether it's an appropriate case for the exercise of this Court's jurisdiction.","start":1414.103,"stop":1421.878,"duration":7.77},{"text":"And that, in our view, is a much more appropriate way to proceed, making that determination at the outset on the basis of the State's complaint, rather than through piecemeal litigation as different non-State parties--","start":1421.878,"stop":1433.577,"duration":11.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, here the complaint was South Carolina's complaint, and these are intervenors on North Carolina's -- on North Carolina's side.","start":1433.577,"stop":1441.653,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's where they were seeking to intervene on North Carolina's side as defendants.","start":1441.653,"stop":1446.399,"duration":4.75},{"text":"That's right.","start":1446.399,"stop":1446.933,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"And as representing the position of the United States, would you address the FERC license that Duke Energy is raising?","start":1446.933,"stop":1457.411,"duration":10.48}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1457.411,"stop":1460.362,"duration":2.95},{"text":"Under section 27 of the Federal Power Act, which is 16 U.S.C. 821, the Power Act does not affect State law water rights.","start":1460.362,"stop":1470.688,"duration":10.33},{"text":"So State law water rights are taken as a given, and it's up to the licensee to have the necessary State water rights, and a FERC license does not in any way alter the distribution of State law property rights in water.","start":1470.688,"stop":1484.399,"duration":13.71},{"text":"And what the commission has said in this case in the final environmental impact statement with respect to Duke's relicensing application, which is available on the commission Web site, it cited section 27 and it said:","start":1484.399,"stop":1496.866,"duration":12.47},{"text":"\"Any license that is issued will not impose requirements, including minimum flows, that infringe on water rights or apportionments. \"","start":1496.866,"stop":1504.485,"duration":7.62},{"text":"So the commission is aware of the pendency of this case.","start":1504.485,"stop":1508.139,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it isn't a matter of infringing on water rights or apportionments.","start":1508.139,"stop":1511.593,"duration":3.45},{"text":"I mean, that does not exclude, it seems to me, the revocation of the license or the denial of a renewal of the license because Duke Power does not have enough water.","start":1511.593,"stop":1522.274,"duration":10.68},{"text":"That wouldn't preclude that, would it?","start":1522.274,"stop":1524.213,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the nature of this proceeding makes that outcome not -- not something that would happen even if South Carolina were to prevail, because what South Carolina is seeking is to get more water flowing downstream to it, and so the -- the licensing conditions, which generally impose minimum flow requirements at each of the various dams operated by Duke, would be easier to satisfy, not harder to satisfy, if South Carolina were -- had an entitlement to get even more water flowing through--","start":1524.213,"stop":1555.935,"duration":31.72}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't understand that.","start":1555.935,"stop":1559.34,"duration":3.4},{"text":"I don't understand that.","start":1559.34,"stop":1559.761,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What happens to North Carolina if it has less water?","start":1559.761,"stop":1561.477,"duration":1.72},{"text":"What does it do with respect to Duke?","start":1561.477,"stop":1564.257,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Duke -- Duke's dams -- the licensing condition is that each dam allow a certain amount of water to flow through, under the current license that they are operating under, and there are different minimum flow requirements under the renewal license that is being sought.","start":1564.257,"stop":1581.282,"duration":17.02},{"text":"But an order in effect requiring that they let more water flow through would not be in conflict with the licensing requirement, but--","start":1581.282,"stop":1590.933,"duration":9.65}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why--","start":1590.933,"stop":1592.4,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And why isn't Duke Power -- why isn't Duke Power on the other side, then?","start":1592.4,"stop":1595.337,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean, I--","start":1595.337,"stop":1598.038,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They have smart lawyers.","start":1598.038,"stop":1599.368,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, they -- I mean, one possibility is, of course, that Duke is -- in addition to obviously being an operator of dams, Duke is a very large consumer of water.","start":1599.368,"stop":1608.8,"duration":9.43},{"text":"In fact, it's the largest consumer of water on the Catawba system because of its coal and nuclear power plants which use water evaporatively for cooling of the power plants.","start":1608.8,"stop":1618.609,"duration":9.81},{"text":"So--","start":1618.609,"stop":1618.999,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, it may also mean it when it has to increase the outflow, the level of its impoundments reduces, and that may affect its ability to generate power, which in turn may -- may affect its license.","start":1618.999,"stop":1635.555,"duration":16.56}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--It -- it may have some effect on its ability to -- to generate power.","start":1635.555,"stop":1642.661,"duration":7.11},{"text":"But that makes it a large industrial user of water, akin to those that the Court referred to in New Jersey v. New York, which were not entitled to intervene.","start":1642.661,"stop":1651.251,"duration":8.59},{"text":"I would also point out in further response, Mr. Chief Justice, to your question, that Duke is a North Carolina corporation, which may be why it's seeking to come in on the North Carolina side of this case.","start":1651.251,"stop":1664.623,"duration":13.37},{"text":"But I -- I want to return to the idea that these kinds of cases are not ordinary cases.","start":1664.623,"stop":1674.914,"duration":10.29},{"text":"They involve sovereign interests, and I think what's important about that is that the interest--","start":1674.914,"stop":1683.407,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Miller, if I -- if I understood your argument, you are saying that Duke's interests are really with South Carolina, or -- to increase the flow.","start":1683.407,"stop":1690.328,"duration":6.92},{"text":"But I would think then it would be North Carolina who would be objecting to their participation in the case rather than South Carolina.","start":1690.328,"stop":1696.856,"duration":6.53},{"text":"And they don't.","start":1696.856,"stop":1700.198,"duration":3.34},{"text":"They -- they welcomed them in, as I remember the papers.","start":1700.198,"stop":1702.729,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Eric D. Miller","textObjs":[{"text":"--As I said, Duke is an operator of thermal power plants that are large consumers of water, and some of those are located in North Carolina.","start":1702.729,"stop":1711.257,"duration":8.53}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1711.257,"stop":1712.911,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Mr. Bartolomucci.","start":1712.911,"stop":1719.208,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: The Special Master correctly concluded that Charlotte, Duke, and the Catawba River Water Supply Project should intervene in this original action.","start":1719.208,"stop":1731.358,"duration":12.15},{"text":"Her recommendation deserves some deference because she is in the best position to know whether these parties would assist her in the adjudication of this complex dispute.","start":1731.358,"stop":1741.416,"duration":10.06}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This is our original jurisdiction.","start":1741.416,"stop":1743.494,"duration":2.08},{"text":"I regard the Special Master as more akin to a law clerk than a district judge.","start":1743.494,"stop":1748.521,"duration":5.03},{"text":"We don't defer to somebody who's an aide that we have assigned to help us gather things here.","start":1748.521,"stop":1754.504,"duration":5.98},{"text":"I think on legal questions of intervention we have to decide de novo.","start":1754.504,"stop":1757.677,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Our claim is not that the Special Master should get deference on legal questions, but she should get deference on -- on the narrow question of whether it would be helpful to her to have these intervenors in the case.","start":1757.677,"stop":1769.593,"duration":11.92},{"text":"She has--","start":1769.593,"stop":1770.264,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But tell me what she said that makes them helpful.","start":1770.264,"stop":1773.856,"duration":3.59},{"text":"What can they provide that couldn't be done by merely an amici submission?","start":1773.856,"stop":1780.15,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, she pointed out, for example, that Duke Energy, which controls the flow of this river and is participating in the FERC proceedings, would establish a -- a direct link between this adjudication and what's going on before the FERC.","start":1780.15,"stop":1794.613,"duration":14.46},{"text":"And of course those two proceedings have -- have a lot of interaction.","start":1794.613,"stop":1797.955,"duration":3.34},{"text":"I think it's also fair to--","start":1797.955,"stop":1800.045,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, your adversary has just said none, according to the terms of the license and what the FERC has said.","start":1800.045,"stop":1806.873,"duration":6.83},{"text":"So why is -- why don't we just take what FERC has said--","start":1806.873,"stop":1811.337,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Oh, I think--","start":1811.337,"stop":1812.383,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--at face value?","start":1812.383,"stop":1813.791,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think FERC has not said that there will be no effect, that there would be no effect upon the licensing proceeding from the original action.","start":1813.791,"stop":1823.816,"duration":10.03},{"text":"There could be a conflict between the decree that comes down, if one comes down in this Court, and the terms of the FERC license.","start":1823.816,"stop":1830.987,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think all FERC said is -- is that nothing in its license would -- would require allocation of water by -- by North Carolina.","start":1830.987,"stop":1839.626,"duration":8.64},{"text":"And that's quite different from whether -- whether a severe reduction in the water that Duke can use would -- would affect the -- the nature of the license given by FERC.","start":1839.626,"stop":1852.883,"duration":13.26}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Duke of course pulled together 69 other stakeholders to join the comprehensive relicensing agreement to -- to smooth FERC's acceptance of -- of the new license.","start":1852.883,"stop":1862.971,"duration":10.09},{"text":"And this original action is -- will pit the two Carolinas, each of which seeks to maximize their share of the river, and those interests work at odds with the CRA, which endorses a compromise middle flow position that -- that neither of the Carolinas seeks to defend in this action.","start":1862.971,"stop":1883.199,"duration":20.23}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, let me tell you what I'm very worried about.","start":1883.199,"stop":1884.556,"duration":1.36},{"text":"This is our original jurisdiction, a delicate jurisdiction that allows us to resolve disputes between sovereign States.","start":1884.556,"stop":1893.005,"duration":8.45},{"text":"And I look out and I see all sorts of private parties intervening in a way that would give them party status.","start":1893.005,"stop":1899.689,"duration":6.68},{"text":"And I think that's compromising what our original jurisdiction is supposed to be about.","start":1899.689,"stop":1904.189,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, private parties and cities have intervened in the past in original actions and have been named as defendants in original actions.","start":1904.189,"stop":1913.233,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But even in the New Jersey v. New York decision, the dissenters there that would have allowed the intervention did say that in general it is unwise to encumber original jurisdiction cases with non-State parties.","start":1913.233,"stop":1934.566,"duration":21.33},{"text":"That was even the dissenters.","start":1934.566,"stop":1938.22,"duration":3.65},{"text":"So you start out with in general it's not wise to let these people come in.","start":1938.22,"stop":1943.921,"duration":5.7},{"text":"And following up on the Chief's question, a State can't be sued without its consent.","start":1943.921,"stop":1952.964,"duration":9.04},{"text":"And it's true here that South Carolina is initiating the action, but it's initiating the action against a sister State.","start":1952.964,"stop":1966.05,"duration":13.09},{"text":"The Special Master's recommendation would require the State to have as its direct adversary three parties who are not a sister State, and that kind of dilutes the notion of original jurisdiction.","start":1966.05,"stop":1987.401,"duration":21.35},{"text":"It's a controversy between two States.","start":1987.401,"stop":1990.462,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in -- Justice Ginsburg, in the case of New Jersey v. New York, New York City was a party defendant, and in this case the City of Charlotte occupies the exact same position as New York City.","start":1990.462,"stop":2004.173,"duration":13.71}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's because the State chose to sue it as a party defendant.","start":2004.173,"stop":2007.015,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"It did, but of course a State can only sue a proper party defendant.","start":2007.015,"stop":2011.718,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Whether the question is intervention or whether it's naming a city as a defendant in an original action, both have to pass the test of is this city or non-State a proper party defendant?","start":2011.718,"stop":2023.104,"duration":11.39}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You're -- all of the intervenors, prospective intervenors, they want to make sure North Carolina doesn't lose water, right?","start":2023.104,"stop":2030.256,"duration":7.15}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is not their exclusive interest.","start":2030.256,"stop":2033.863,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, their -- well, they want to reduce South Carolina's claim on the water.","start":2033.863,"stop":2036.831,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2036.831,"stop":2037.256,"duration":0.43},{"text":"Duke Energy, for example, doesn't have an interest in maximizing the flow on the North Carolina side of the river.","start":2037.256,"stop":2043.44,"duration":6.18},{"text":"Duke's -- Duke Energy's interest is in preserving the -- the flow compromise reflected in the CRA.","start":2043.44,"stop":2050.03,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- to the extent they have differing interests, why aren't those interests fully satisfied by amicus participation?","start":2050.03,"stop":2056.87,"duration":6.84}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when -- when South Carolina first opposed, for example, Charlotte's motion to intervene, it said: Oh, Charlotte, you can file an amicus brief as to any dispositive motion.","start":2056.87,"stop":2068.413,"duration":11.54},{"text":"Well, that kind of amicus participation is vastly different from being able to shape the record on which the -- the key issues in this case are finally decided.","start":2068.413,"stop":2077.488,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Shape the record, but intervention status would give you the right to appeal, right?","start":2077.488,"stop":2081.766,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"It would allow us to seek leave to file exceptions to an--","start":2081.766,"stop":2085.451,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, and appeal the normal case.","start":2085.451,"stop":2087.202,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2087.202,"stop":2087.81,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's my question.","start":2087.81,"stop":2088.512,"duration":0.7},{"text":"If we grant intervention in this type of case and there is no reason it would be three -- I mean, in the next case, it could be 20 different intervenors, and they are filing exceptions every other week that we have to review and adjudicate because they are not bound by whether or not the State that is on their side wants to file exceptions.","start":2088.512,"stop":2107.49,"duration":18.98}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me say two things, Mr. Chief Justice: If the proposed decree affects the interests of Charlotte or the joint venture or Duke, I think they ought to be allowed to file exceptions, which this Court can grant leave or not.","start":2107.49,"stop":2119.75,"duration":12.26},{"text":"As to the specter of 20 possible intervenors--","start":2119.75,"stop":2123.326,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So how does that get us to avoid involvement in interstate -- intrastate disputes over water use?","start":2123.326,"stop":2131.448,"duration":8.12},{"text":"That just drags us right into your problems among your water users.","start":2131.448,"stop":2135.726,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, South Carolina and the United States present this vision of an equitable apportionment action in which the Special Master simply divides up the flow of the river, and then it's up to each State to subdivide among its users.","start":2135.726,"stop":2148.505,"duration":12.78},{"text":"But that is not what has happened in equitable apportionment cases.","start":2148.505,"stop":2151.489,"duration":2.98},{"text":"In New Jersey v. New York, for example, this Court entered a decree, which enjoined the flow of the Delaware River to New York City above a specified level.","start":2151.489,"stop":2161.592,"duration":10.1},{"text":"I think 411 cubic feet per second.","start":2161.592,"stop":2164.466,"duration":2.87},{"text":"And -- and that is the kind of decree that South Carolina, I believe, is seeking in this case.","start":2164.466,"stop":2170.495,"duration":6.03},{"text":"If you look at paragraph 2 of South Carolina's prayer for relief, they want an injunction against the interbasin transfers currently being carried -- carried out by Charlotte and the joint venture.","start":2170.495,"stop":2181.194,"duration":10.7},{"text":"So this--","start":2181.194,"stop":2181.896,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And North Carolina, as a sovereign State, can represent the interests of its constituents as it sees fit.","start":2181.896,"stop":2188.394,"duration":6.5},{"text":"You and your fellow prospective intervenors just have to do what citizens do all the time, which is convince North Carolina, one, and you can help them, to get as much water as they can; and, two, when they get it or if they lose it, whatever they are left it, to give it to you, rather than the other parties.","start":2188.394,"stop":2204.436,"duration":16.04}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, as to Duke -- Mr. Chief Justice, I have explained, Duke's interest is not in maximizing the share -- North Carolina's share of the river.","start":2204.436,"stop":2211.946,"duration":7.51},{"text":"The joint venture of the Catawba River Water Supply Project is not represented by either State because it's a bi-State entity.","start":2211.946,"stop":2219.772,"duration":7.83},{"text":"Neither -- and both of the Carolinas is -- are affirmatively hostile to part of the operations of the joint venture.","start":2219.772,"stop":2227.627,"duration":7.86},{"text":"When the joint venture--","start":2227.627,"stop":2229.019,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then that's--","start":2229.019,"stop":2229.596,"duration":0.58},{"text":"then I just wonder why you are here in an original action.","start":2229.596,"stop":2232.485,"duration":2.89},{"text":"What you are saying is they have all sorts of different interests, and it just -- they get to skip district court.","start":2232.485,"stop":2237.512,"duration":5.03},{"text":"They get to skip the court of appeals.","start":2237.512,"stop":2238.764,"duration":1.25},{"text":"They can just come right in here, as if they were a State, and participate in the case.","start":2238.764,"stop":2244.321,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Mr. Chief Justice, I think this -- this is not a novel proposition.","start":2244.321,"stop":2249.66,"duration":5.34},{"text":"The City of Port Arthur was allowed to intervene in the case of Texas v. Louisiana.","start":2249.66,"stop":2254.067,"duration":4.41},{"text":"Five Indian tribes intervened in Arizona v. California, and New York City was allowed to be a party defendant in the New Jersey case, even though the Court could have dismissed it from the case, as it did to the Indiana citizens in--","start":2254.067,"stop":2268.996,"duration":14.93}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You are advocating a rule that says, almost, you have a right to intervene because you have an interest that won't be adequately represented.","start":2268.996,"stop":2282.879,"duration":13.88}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--We--","start":2282.879,"stop":2283.492,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that your position?","start":2283.492,"stop":2284.756,"duration":1.26},{"text":"Then what happens to the Special Master who says, no, I don't want all you guys here?","start":2284.756,"stop":2288.959,"duration":4.2},{"text":"How do we say that that master abused his or her discretion by saying no?","start":2288.959,"stop":2297.639,"duration":8.68}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--We are saying that the Special Master got it right, when she said that you have to show a compelling interest that's not properly represented by a party State, and she applied the New Jersey v. New York test, finding, at page 27 of her report, that neither Charlotte nor the joint venture are properly represented.","start":2297.639,"stop":2316.508,"duration":18.87}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So you see the issue before us as being was she right or wrong, even though Nevada said -- I'm sorry -- that North Carolina said that it was going to adequately represent each of these interests, but that just wasn't correct?","start":2316.508,"stop":2330.988,"duration":14.48}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the question is--","start":2330.988,"stop":2331.908,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That North Carolina is not telling us the truth?","start":2331.908,"stop":2333.94,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think the question is, should the Court accept the Special Master's recommendation?","start":2333.94,"stop":2338.795,"duration":4.86},{"text":"And I would disagree with South Carolina, when it says that she applied the wrong legal test.","start":2338.795,"stop":2344.73,"duration":5.93},{"text":"She did apply New Jersey v. New York.","start":2344.73,"stop":2347.277,"duration":2.55},{"text":"She did find that the intervenors were not properly represented by the party States.","start":2347.277,"stop":2351.416,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't--","start":2351.416,"stop":2352.242,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"The intervenors -- the intervenors are users of the water from the river?","start":2352.242,"stop":2357.913,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"But not mere users.","start":2357.913,"stop":2358.989,"duration":1.08},{"text":"Their status is special.","start":2358.989,"stop":2361.13,"duration":2.14},{"text":"Duke, of course, is unique.","start":2361.13,"stop":2362.565,"duration":1.43},{"text":"It controls the flow of the river, and there's no one else like Duke on the Catawba.","start":2362.565,"stop":2366.301,"duration":3.74},{"text":"The other two intervenors are the cause of the harm for which South Carolina seeks injunctive relief.","start":2366.301,"stop":2372.658,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- because they use a lot of water.","start":2372.658,"stop":2375.406,"duration":2.75},{"text":"And my question is: How do we decide once we say -- beyond the Special Master can let these people in with party status -- what users can come in where, obviously, we are not going to allow all users of the river water to come in, so which ones can and which ones can't?","start":2375.406,"stop":2398.207,"duration":22.8}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, our position is not that mere users of water or all users of water may intervene in original action.","start":2398.207,"stop":2405.846,"duration":7.64},{"text":"You have to show a compelling interest that's not properly represented, and that's going to depend upon the specific facts of the case.","start":2405.846,"stop":2413.406,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And is it automatic then?","start":2413.406,"stop":2414.483,"duration":1.08},{"text":"Is it automatic then?","start":2414.483,"stop":2416.23,"duration":1.75},{"text":"Or is it just that, when that condition is met, the Special Master can permit the intervention?","start":2416.23,"stop":2423.432,"duration":7.2}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Justice Scalia.","start":2423.432,"stop":2424.961,"duration":1.53},{"text":"I would say it's not automatic because there are some other considerations the Special Master can bring to bear.","start":2424.961,"stop":2429.71,"duration":4.75},{"text":"For example, timeliness -- you can't show up 20 years after the litigation has started, like the City of Philadelphia, and expect to get in.","start":2429.71,"stop":2436.831,"duration":7.12},{"text":"You--","start":2436.831,"stop":2437.88,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And, also, how helpful the intervention will be to the management of the case.","start":2437.88,"stop":2442.75,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct.","start":2442.75,"stop":2443.16,"duration":0.41},{"text":"Or, conversely, how--","start":2443.16,"stop":2444.081,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And, of course, the Special Master's determination of that is not final.","start":2444.081,"stop":2446.752,"duration":2.67},{"text":"It's ultimately up to us.","start":2446.752,"stop":2448.172,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's correct.","start":2448.172,"stop":2449.47,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But it is a discretionary intervention you are arguing for, not a mandatory one.","start":2449.47,"stop":2452.765,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"It is discretionary, and if -- if the Special Master believes that -- that this complex multiyear water rights dispute would be aided by the presence of a -- of a limited number of intervenors who have a very special interest in the case, then that's something that, for institutional--","start":2452.765,"stop":2468.819,"duration":16.05}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, what's special about it?","start":2468.819,"stop":2469.899,"duration":1.08},{"text":"I mean, let's say I own a little farm on the banks of the Catawba, and I take water out to -- so the cows have something to drink, why does Charlotte get a special status just because they take a lot?","start":2469.899,"stop":2480.346,"duration":10.45},{"text":"I'm affected by how much water runs through there.","start":2480.346,"stop":2482.83,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Charlotte has special status because South Carolina seeks specific relief -- injunctive relief -- against Charlotte's interbasin transfer.","start":2482.83,"stop":2492.434,"duration":9.6}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and that relief will affect how much water is available for me to draw out and use on my farm.","start":2492.434,"stop":2497.808,"duration":5.37},{"text":"That's a compelling interest.","start":2497.808,"stop":2499.23,"duration":1.42},{"text":"I -- you know, in times of drought, this water barely trickles by, and, if it's cut back, the farm is going to go down.","start":2499.23,"stop":2507.993,"duration":8.76},{"text":"It seems to me that, when you say they have a special interest, you are just saying they have got a big interest.","start":2507.993,"stop":2511.787,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not just that it's -- it's a big interest, and it surely is, but they are singled out in South Carolina's complaint, and injunctive relief is sought against them, which, I think, brings into the play the rule this Court announced in Kentucky v. Indiana, which is that, if a plaintiff or plaintiff State in an original action is seeking relief against a citizen of a State, that citizen ought to have an opportunity to come into the litigation and defend its interests.","start":2511.787,"stop":2539.009,"duration":27.22},{"text":"That's what Charlotte is seeking in this case.","start":2539.009,"stop":2541.525,"duration":2.52},{"text":"The joint venture, of course, is not represented by either State fully because both States are hostile to at least part of what the joint venture does.","start":2541.525,"stop":2551.706,"duration":10.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's say the interest -- the dispute is really in effect between company ABC in North Carolina and company XYZ in South Carolina.","start":2551.706,"stop":2559.423,"duration":7.72},{"text":"I mean, do we -- we would not accept an original action if they sued each other, right?","start":2559.423,"stop":2564.158,"duration":4.74}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"No -- well, of course--","start":2564.158,"stop":2565.577,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do we let them just use the States as, you know, a faade to get into this Court and have their dispute adjudicated here?","start":2565.577,"stop":2572.511,"duration":6.93}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":2572.511,"stop":2572.823,"duration":0.31},{"text":"As in Kentucky v. Indiana, if there are improper parties in original action, they -- they can be dismissed, but I think it's noteworthy that the Court allowed the New Jersey litigation to proceed with New York City as a party defendant.","start":2572.823,"stop":2586.864,"duration":14.04},{"text":"And Charlotte's position is truly indistinguishable from the position of -- of New York City in that action, with -- with the sole exception that Charlotte seeks to intervene, whereas New York City was named as a party defendant.","start":2586.864,"stop":2599.378,"duration":12.51},{"text":"South Carolina invokes the principle that it is the master of its complaint, and we would agree with that, in part.","start":2599.378,"stop":2606.172,"duration":6.79},{"text":"A plaintiff is the master of the allegations in claims it seeks to make, but a plaintiff is not a master of the universe of -- of interests that -- that may be affected by the lawsuit they have -- they have brought.","start":2606.172,"stop":2618.057,"duration":11.88},{"text":"That's--","start":2618.057,"stop":2618.541,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think the same -- the same test applies to the appropriateness of naming a private party defendant, as you would urge for intervention by a private party defendant?","start":2618.541,"stop":2632.283,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2632.283,"stop":2632.802,"duration":0.52},{"text":"I think there would be a very similar analysis.","start":2632.802,"stop":2635.345,"duration":2.54},{"text":"I think that the question whether a proposed defendant -- and of course, you need leave from this Court to file an original action or to name someone as a defendant in an original action.","start":2635.345,"stop":2645.483,"duration":10.14},{"text":"I think, in both cases, it raises the question: Is -- is this entity a proper party defendant or is the entity a proper intervenor?","start":2645.483,"stop":2653.337,"duration":7.85},{"text":"I think it's a similar analysis.","start":2653.337,"stop":2655.01,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask this question: In what respect does the relief sought against the city differ from the relief sought against the State?","start":2655.01,"stop":2661.896,"duration":6.89}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"In this respect, Justice Stevens: The -- the complaint prays for North Carolina to stop authorizing the interbasin transfers being carried out by Charlotte and the joint venture.","start":2661.896,"stop":2676.437,"duration":14.54},{"text":"But -- but Charlotte and the joint venture are the entities whose primary conduct, if you will, would be affected by that injunction.","start":2676.437,"stop":2684.935,"duration":8.5},{"text":"They are the parties who are carrying out the interbasin transfers, and they would have to stop those transfers if -- if authorization was withdrawn by North Carolina.","start":2684.935,"stop":2693.837,"duration":8.9}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Wouldn't it -- would it be surprising if the Special Master recommended that all the issue that she was going to address was the relative equitable apportionment between North Carolina and South Carolina, and even though South Carolina wanted an injunction directed against the City of Charlotte, that's up to North Carolina?","start":2693.837,"stop":2711.798,"duration":17.96},{"text":"North Carolina can divvy up its water however it wants.","start":2711.798,"stop":2714.282,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would not be surprising if she came down -- if she were to come down with a decree, it would not be surprising that -- that it would decide whether or not to allow Charlotte's interbasin transfers to continue.","start":2714.282,"stop":2727.264,"duration":12.98},{"text":"Because that's -- that was much like what was decided, for example, in New Jersey v. New York.","start":2727.264,"stop":2732.337,"duration":5.07},{"text":"There was the proposed diversion of water to New York City, and the Court there ultimately entered a partial injunction that banned flows to New York City above a certain level.","start":2732.337,"stop":2744.176,"duration":11.84},{"text":"So--","start":2744.176,"stop":2745.1,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in -- in deciding what's equitable as between the two States, I guess the -- the Court, ultimately, and the Special Master, initially, will have to decide what uses of water by one State or the other are not equitable uses--","start":2745.1,"stop":2761.559,"duration":16.46}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--And, Justice Scalia--","start":2761.559,"stop":2762.698,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--and go beyond what is reasonable.","start":2762.698,"stop":2763.685,"duration":0.99},{"text":"So I don't see how you could decide the case without deciding whether especially particularly massive uses are appropriate or not.","start":2763.685,"stop":2773.383,"duration":9.7}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Not just massive.","start":2773.383,"stop":2774.65,"duration":1.27},{"text":"There's -- it's no accident that South Carolina focuses upon these interbasin transfers, because they inflict a special injury, in South Carolina's view.","start":2774.65,"stop":2783.365,"duration":8.71},{"text":"The interbasin transfers take water out of the river basin, and -- and so it doesn't come back to South Carolina within the basin.","start":2783.365,"stop":2793.064,"duration":9.7},{"text":"Other types of uses of water are non-consumptive, in the sense that the water can be treated and eventually gets to South Carolina within that basin.","start":2793.064,"stop":2801.826,"duration":8.76},{"text":"But South Carolina has targeted these interbasin transfers because they are entirely, 100 percent consumptive, in the sense that -- that once the water has left the basin--","start":2801.826,"stop":2811.711,"duration":9.88}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Dead losses to South Carolina.","start":2811.711,"stop":2813.571,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--it does -- it does not come back.","start":2813.571,"stop":2814.96,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the percentage, approximately, of the river that flows into South Carolina that the three intervenors account for?","start":2814.96,"stop":2823.768,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think I have done that math, Justice Breyer.","start":2823.768,"stop":2828.034,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, about.","start":2828.034,"stop":2828.534,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2828.534,"stop":2829.345,"duration":0.81},{"text":"I can tell you that Charlotte's authorization is -- is 33 million gallons a day.","start":2829.345,"stop":2836.262,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Out of what?","start":2836.262,"stop":2836.968,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the flow of the River -- the minimum flow of the river, under the -- under the CRA is 1100 cubic feet per second, so unfortunately you'd have to -- you'd have to convert from cfs to--","start":2836.968,"stop":2851.369,"duration":14.4}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean, do they account for, like -- there's a certain amount of water in dispute.","start":2851.369,"stop":2855.6,"duration":4.23},{"text":"There are some people who want to intervene.","start":2855.6,"stop":2858.038,"duration":2.44},{"text":"Are the people who intervene -- do they account more like 1 percent of all the water that's in dispute, or do they account for more like 50 percent?","start":2858.038,"stop":2865.532,"duration":7.49},{"text":"That seems like a pretty relevant question to me.","start":2865.532,"stop":2868.39,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I -- it's a significant proportion.","start":2868.39,"stop":2870.437,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"You must have some idea.","start":2870.437,"stop":2870.921,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a significant proportion.","start":2870.921,"stop":2872.142,"duration":1.22},{"text":"It's not--","start":2872.142,"stop":2872.844,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, significant -- is that more like 3 percent, or is it more like 90 percent?","start":2872.844,"stop":2877.059,"duration":4.22},{"text":"I mean, nobody has ever bothered to look at that in this whole case?","start":2877.059,"stop":2880.182,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I haven't done that calculation.","start":2880.182,"stop":2883.852,"duration":3.67},{"text":"I will say that they are significant enough that South Carolina seeks a specific injunction against those interbasin transfers.","start":2883.852,"stop":2890.009,"duration":6.16}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And I guess it depends on what you mean by the water in dispute.","start":2890.009,"stop":2892.867,"duration":2.86},{"text":"If the main gravamen of the complaint is interbasin transfers, they -- they occupy a huge proportion of that.","start":2892.867,"stop":2900.878,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"And as the Special Master read it, IBTs are--","start":2900.878,"stop":2904.594,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, that's -- I agree.","start":2904.594,"stop":2905.702,"duration":1.11},{"text":"That's a good point, but -- so what percentage if -- what percentage of the interbasin transfers do they account for?","start":2905.702,"stop":2912.152,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, they represent, actually, 100 percent of the interbasin transfers--","start":2912.152,"stop":2916.62,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2916.62,"stop":2916.932,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"--being carried out.","start":2916.932,"stop":2917.681,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So insofar -- so insofar as what they are after is interbasin transfers, just what Justice Scalia said is correct.","start":2917.681,"stop":2923.804,"duration":6.12},{"text":"These are the interbasin transfer people.","start":2923.804,"stop":2925.553,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"These are the -- the IBTs at issue.","start":2925.553,"stop":2927.285,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's helpful.","start":2927.285,"stop":2927.878,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Counsel.","start":2927.878,"stop":2928.818,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"H. Christopher Bartolomucci","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2928.818,"stop":2929.379,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Browning.","start":2929.379,"stop":2937.892,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: Let me turn to two questions that Justice Scalia asked Mr. Frederick, but I think his response needs clarification from North Carolina's perspective.","start":2937.892,"stop":2950.869,"duration":12.98},{"text":"The first question dealt with Maryland v. Louisiana, and Mr. Frederick responded that that case, in which 17 pipeline companies were permitted to intervene -- according to Mr. Frederick, the States in that case did not serve as parens patriae with regard to those 17 pipeline companies.","start":2950.869,"stop":2970.613,"duration":19.74},{"text":"That is factually incorrect.","start":2970.613,"stop":2972.5,"duration":1.89},{"text":"In that case, two of those pipeline companies -- the Michigan-Wisconsin Pipeline Company was a resident of the State of Michigan, one of the complaining States in that case, as well as the National Gas Pipeline Company of America was an Illinois corporation.","start":2972.5,"stop":2991.323,"duration":18.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Maryland v. Louisiana involved a specific tax on specific companies, and they were allowed to intervene.","start":2991.323,"stop":2997.821,"duration":6.5},{"text":"This is not that.","start":2997.821,"stop":2999.147,"duration":1.33},{"text":"This is a question of how the equitable apportionment of the water is going to be, and North Carolina can do with the water whatever it will.","start":2999.147,"stop":3006.005,"duration":6.86},{"text":"It strikes me as very different than Maryland v. Louisiana.","start":3006.005,"stop":3009.83,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, in Maryland v. Louisiana, that was a taxation case, a case that goes to a fundamental interest of the States, the power of taxation.","start":3009.83,"stop":3020.561,"duration":10.73}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Did -- did the decree only apply to taxing these particular companies?","start":3020.561,"stop":3025.135,"duration":4.57},{"text":"Could the -- could the State have taxed other companies after the decree issued?","start":3025.135,"stop":3028.606,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, as the Plaintiff States were seeking to attack the Louisiana tax at issue.","start":3028.606,"stop":3035.93,"duration":7.32},{"text":"So it would have general applicability.","start":3035.93,"stop":3039.069,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As -- as the allocation would in this case, presumably.","start":3039.069,"stop":3041.975,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't -- and that question--","start":3041.975,"stop":3044.396,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that yes or no?","start":3044.396,"stop":3044.849,"duration":0.45},{"text":"I -- you say yes, it would have general applicability.","start":3044.849,"stop":3046.988,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Your Honor.","start":3046.988,"stop":3048.033,"duration":1.05},{"text":"Yes, Justice Scalia.","start":3048.033,"stop":3049.253,"duration":1.22},{"text":"Your Honor, South Carolina has said that this case is about consumption of water in toto.","start":3049.253,"stop":3056.171,"duration":6.92},{"text":"But when you look at their bill of complaint, that is simply not the case.","start":3056.171,"stop":3060.964,"duration":4.79},{"text":"When you look at the question presented in their leave for -- their motion for leave to file a bill of complaint, it starts out whether North Carolina's interbasin transfer statute is invalid under the Supremacy Clause of the United States Constitution.","start":3060.964,"stop":3076.477,"duration":15.51},{"text":"And when you look at the allegations in the bill of complaint, it is specifically focused on interbasin transfers.","start":3076.477,"stop":3083.644,"duration":7.17},{"text":"It asserts that they are inequitable, and it is seeking injunctive relief with respect to those interbasin transfers.","start":3083.644,"stop":3090.125,"duration":6.48},{"text":"We--","start":3090.125,"stop":3090.924,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how is just this involved?","start":3090.924,"stop":3091.439,"duration":0.51},{"text":"Is there -- because I am amazed that this is now coming to me for the first time.","start":3091.439,"stop":3094.468,"duration":3.03},{"text":"All this case is about is interbasin transfers and that you account for 100 percent of them, you three.","start":3094.468,"stop":3100.602,"duration":6.13},{"text":"Is that -- is that right?","start":3100.602,"stop":3102.072,"duration":1.47},{"text":"Because I suspect in, like, 5 minutes, somebody might tell me it's not right.","start":3102.072,"stop":3106.366,"duration":4.29},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":3106.366,"stop":3106.678,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, there are -- there are very few interbasin transfers.","start":3106.678,"stop":3109.896,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- that's not my question.","start":3109.896,"stop":3111.69,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3111.69,"stop":3111.986,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I want -- I'm trying -- look, if Alaska sued California and the complaint was we want San Francisco back, San Francisco might have a right to intervene.","start":3111.986,"stop":3120.467,"duration":8.48},{"text":"But if it was about California generally, maybe they wouldn't.","start":3120.467,"stop":3124.343,"duration":3.88},{"text":"So what I want to know is, what's the water that is at issue in this complaint and how much of the water that is at issue in this complaint do the three intervenors account for?","start":3124.343,"stop":3134.135,"duration":9.79},{"text":"That seems like a fairly simple empirical question.","start":3134.135,"stop":3137.321,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3137.321,"stop":3137.711,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I'm trying to get the answer to.","start":3137.711,"stop":3139.102,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3139.102,"stop":3140.21,"duration":1.11},{"text":"The -- the two intervenors that have interbasin transfers account for the vast majority of the water that is consumed as a result of an interbasin transfer.","start":3140.21,"stop":3153.312,"duration":13.1},{"text":"In the 2006 study that was done by Duke Energy, the largest interbasin transfer is the City of Charlotte at 9 million gallons per day.","start":3153.312,"stop":3163.513,"duration":10.2},{"text":"The second--","start":3163.513,"stop":3164.231,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, my basic concern is that -- and I will let you finish if there is more to the answer.","start":3164.231,"stop":3169.604,"duration":5.37},{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":3169.604,"stop":3169.916,"duration":0.31},{"text":"Private parties are going to hijack our original jurisdiction, and it was highlighted for me when I read your motion, the motion of private parties for divided argument.","start":3169.916,"stop":3180.27,"duration":10.35},{"text":"Your proposal was that they be divided 10, 10, and 10.","start":3180.27,"stop":3183.55,"duration":3.28},{"text":"You didn't even want to be here.","start":3183.55,"stop":3184.922,"duration":1.37},{"text":"As they view the case and as you view the case, it's got so little to do with the State that the State didn't even want to come here and argue the case.","start":3184.922,"stop":3192.733,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, that was an accommodation from the State of North Carolina with respect to the intervenors.","start":3192.733,"stop":3198.747,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You thought their participation here before this Court on a question in original jurisdiction was more important than yours, and you represent the State.","start":3198.747,"stop":3206.837,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the intervention motion directly affects each of these intervenors, and they have a right to be heard with respect to that intervention motion.","start":3206.837,"stop":3215.927,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why can't you represent them?","start":3215.927,"stop":3216.972,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":3216.972,"stop":3217.596,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They are your constituents.","start":3217.596,"stop":3218.719,"duration":1.12},{"text":"You are the State.","start":3218.719,"stop":3219.675,"duration":0.96},{"text":"You are coming here directly, not even going to district court, and you seem to be ceding your sovereignty over to them.","start":3219.675,"stop":3226.25,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, we do not believe that we are ceding our sovereignty.","start":3226.25,"stop":3228.796,"duration":2.55},{"text":"With respect to Duke Energy and the Catawba River Water Supply Project, North Carolina does not and cannot adequately represent their interests with respect to Duke Energy.","start":3228.796,"stop":3240.214,"duration":11.42}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":3240.214,"stop":3242.759,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay, with respect to Duke Energy: Duke is -- has 11 dams in North and South Carolina.","start":3242.759,"stop":3249.88,"duration":7.12},{"text":"As a result of those dams, Duke Energy controls the flow of the river into South Carolina.","start":3249.88,"stop":3255.534,"duration":5.65},{"text":"As--","start":3255.534,"stop":3256.299,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But you are going to defend all of their interests as it affects North Carolina, right?","start":3256.299,"stop":3262.924,"duration":6.63},{"text":"You are not incapable of protecting their North Carolina interests.","start":3262.924,"stop":3266.032,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, their interests are inseparable, specifically with regard to Duke Energy.","start":3266.032,"stop":3269.967,"duration":3.93},{"text":"Duke negotiated, over a period of several years, a comprehensive relicensing agreement, with various agencies of North Carolina, various agencies of South Carolina, and stakeholders up and down this river.","start":3269.967,"stop":3284.274,"duration":14.31},{"text":"As a result of that negotiated agreement, there was -- the CRA was put in place, which is essentially a request that FERC issue a license in accordance with the provisions of that agreement.","start":3284.274,"stop":3298.393,"duration":14.12},{"text":"That agreement would set a minimum flow of water into South Carolina that is much, much higher than the previous license.","start":3298.393,"stop":3305.889,"duration":7.5},{"text":"Now, South Carolina has come into Court and has attacked that agreement.","start":3305.889,"stop":3310.343,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Duke has a very real and substantial interest with respect to that agreement.","start":3310.343,"stop":3314.87,"duration":4.53},{"text":"But--","start":3314.87,"stop":3315.384,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What is -- what's the interest of North Carolina?","start":3315.384,"stop":3316.917,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":3316.917,"stop":3317.65,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You are standing there telling me why Duke has an interest.","start":3317.65,"stop":3320.353,"duration":2.7},{"text":"What's North Carolina's interest?","start":3320.353,"stop":3321.726,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, North Carolina will defend these interbasin transfers, but with respect to Duke Energy, we are not aligned with Duke Energy because Duke has a very real interest in preserving--","start":3321.726,"stop":3331.737,"duration":10.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So oppose their intervention.","start":3331.737,"stop":3333.612,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, we believe that they have a right to be heard because of their compelling interests that are affected in this case.","start":3333.612,"stop":3341.06,"duration":7.45},{"text":"South Carolina is seeking to change the CRA, to have a flow of water that is much higher than is set out in the CRA.","start":3341.06,"stop":3349.775,"duration":8.72},{"text":"Although North Carolina supports--","start":3349.775,"stop":3351.401,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't it your interest to -- to resist that?","start":3351.401,"stop":3353.273,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Your Honor.","start":3353.273,"stop":3354.618,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Not only are we resisting that--","start":3354.618,"stop":3356.116,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"And your interest is to defend the CRA, right?","start":3356.116,"stop":3357.352,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, North Carolina will resist having South Carolina have a greater flow of water than--","start":3357.352,"stop":3363.88,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You haven't answered my question.","start":3363.88,"stop":3365.034,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry.","start":3365.034,"stop":3365.346,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it in your interest not to support the CRA?","start":3365.346,"stop":3369.145,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3369.145,"stop":3369.831,"duration":0.69},{"text":"It is in our interest because even--","start":3369.831,"stop":3371.438,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You would like -- you would like, in this litigation against the two States, for the Special Master to undo the -- your obligations under the CRA?","start":3371.438,"stop":3381.093,"duration":9.65}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That will, ultimately, be our request in this case because South Carolina has attacked that agreement.","start":3381.093,"stop":3385.198,"duration":4.11},{"text":"From North Carolina's perspective, South Carolina is receiving much more water under this negotiated agreement than they could ever hope to achieve in an equitable apportionment action.","start":3385.198,"stop":3395.774,"duration":10.58},{"text":"So at the end of the day, we will be asking this Court to issue a decree that sets a flow of water less than--","start":3395.774,"stop":3401.912,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So you are prepared to tell us right now -- this is what you are saying to us: We will not represent the interest of Duke?","start":3401.912,"stop":3408.159,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--We will not represent the interest of Duke, given their--","start":3408.159,"stop":3410.565,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you prepared to say the same thing with respect to your city?","start":3410.565,"stop":3413.735,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--With respect--","start":3413.735,"stop":3415.092,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"And to your -- and to the CRWSP?","start":3415.092,"stop":3418.497,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--With respect to the city, we have said in our briefs that we will defend this interbasin transfer.","start":3418.497,"stop":3425.105,"duration":6.61},{"text":"We believe that we will represent the City of Charlotte with respect to that regard, but we also support their intervention motions because we do not believe that it would result in them impeaching the interests of North Carolina.","start":3425.105,"stop":3438.754,"duration":13.65},{"text":"And more importantly, the Special Master got it right, that there is -- this is a specific attack on the City of Charlotte and its unique interests.","start":3438.754,"stop":3448.659,"duration":9.91},{"text":"It is seeking injunctive relief that will cripple the largest city in North and South Carolina.","start":3448.659,"stop":3453.39,"duration":4.73}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it's an attack on -- if it's an attack on Charlotte, I would expect the State to be standing there protecting it and not feel that they can't do that without Charlotte, itself, coming into the case.","start":3453.39,"stop":3462.9,"duration":9.51}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we will defend this interbasin transfer, but the fact of the matter is injunctive relief is sought as against Charlotte, and there is something to be said for fairness in allowing that entity to be present in this Court.","start":3462.9,"stop":3476.256,"duration":13.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you--","start":3476.256,"stop":3476.724,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, turning--","start":3476.724,"stop":3477.472,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--Are you prepared to say that you are not adequately defending the interest of the CRWSP?","start":3477.472,"stop":3482.44,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct, Your Honor, that that is an interstate entity.","start":3482.44,"stop":3485.408,"duration":2.97},{"text":"It -- its interests have been expressly attacked, the interbasin transfer.","start":3485.408,"stop":3490.782,"duration":5.37},{"text":"South Carolina singles it out in the bill of complaint.","start":3490.782,"stop":3494.529,"duration":3.75},{"text":"What's more important--","start":3494.529,"stop":3496.311,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You haven't answered my question.","start":3496.311,"stop":3497.902,"duration":1.59},{"text":"You said, with Duke, that you won't support--","start":3497.902,"stop":3500.262,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":3500.262,"stop":3501.057,"duration":0.79},{"text":"We--","start":3501.057,"stop":3501.903,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--them.","start":3501.903,"stop":3502.325,"duration":0.42},{"text":"Are you not going to support this -- the joint venture in property?","start":3502.325,"stop":3506.228,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--We -- we cannot represent the interests of the joint venture.","start":3506.228,"stop":3508.588,"duration":2.36},{"text":"They have an interbasin transfer, pursuant to the North Carolina statute for Union County.","start":3508.588,"stop":3514.304,"duration":5.72},{"text":"But what the complaint doesn't disclose is that the other half of that joint venture also has an interbasin transfer with respect to Lancaster County, South Carolina.","start":3514.304,"stop":3524.345,"duration":10.04},{"text":"So South Carolina can hardly attack the Union County interbasin transfer while simultaneously defending the Lancaster County, South Carolina, interbasin transfer.","start":3524.345,"stop":3535.638,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's go back to the question of couldn't the Special Master receive the information she wants if these three entities come in as amici?","start":3535.638,"stop":3548.101,"duration":12.46},{"text":"Coming in as intervenors, they have full party status.","start":3548.101,"stop":3551.459,"duration":3.36},{"text":"They can engage in discovery.","start":3551.459,"stop":3553.88,"duration":2.42},{"text":"They can protract the case.","start":3553.88,"stop":3555.643,"duration":1.76},{"text":"They can appeal any adverse judgment.","start":3555.643,"stop":3559.254,"duration":3.61},{"text":"Why isn't the most reasonable accommodation to say, well, we will listen to you, but we are not going to give you full party status?","start":3559.254,"stop":3567.45,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Christopher G. Browning, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, if that were the -- the standard, there would never be intervention motions in any of these proceedings.","start":3567.45,"stop":3573.701,"duration":6.25},{"text":"The fact of the matter is that these entities have unique interests, and with respect to two of those interests -- Duke Energy and the Catawba River Water Supply Project -- their interests are not represented by either State.","start":3573.701,"stop":3586.851,"duration":13.15},{"text":"All three of them have been expressly attacked in the complaint, and fairness dictates they should have an opportunity to be heard.","start":3586.851,"stop":3594.412,"duration":7.56},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3594.412,"stop":3594.973,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3594.973,"stop":3595.504,"duration":0.53},{"text":"Mr. Frederick, you have 2 minutes.","start":3595.504,"stop":3597.458,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"I have four points, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3597.458,"stop":3600.269,"duration":2.81},{"text":"First--","start":3600.269,"stop":3600.846,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Tell me, are you seeking injunctive relief out of any of the three intervenors?","start":3600.846,"stop":3608.153,"duration":7.31}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":3608.153,"stop":3608.621,"duration":0.47},{"text":"We seek an injunction enjoining the interbasin transfer statute to the extent it exceeds North Carolina's equitable apportionment.","start":3608.621,"stop":3619.01,"duration":10.39},{"text":"We are here to get our fair share of the river vis--vis North Carolina.","start":3619.01,"stop":3624.975,"duration":5.96},{"text":"And Duke's CRA application expressly disclaims any -- any ability to go into the interbasin transfer.","start":3624.975,"stop":3633.676,"duration":8.7},{"text":"That's at page 20, footnote 14, of our motion for leave to file exceptions.","start":3633.676,"stop":3638.582,"duration":4.91},{"text":"The FERC has said it will not affect, in giving its license, the equitable apportionment action now pending before you.","start":3638.582,"stop":3646.497,"duration":7.91},{"text":"In Duke's CRA, at paragraph 39.9, it says it does not affect State water uses.","start":3646.497,"stop":3653.886,"duration":7.39},{"text":"So the only issue here is whether or not those expressed disclaimers should be given effect when South Carolina is simply seeking to determine, as between the two States, the rights.","start":3653.886,"stop":3667.96,"duration":14.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But it affects the agreement on which the license is based.","start":3667.96,"stop":3671.568,"duration":3.61},{"text":"The license was based upon a very hard negotiated agreement among a number of entities.","start":3671.568,"stop":3677.721,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"The license hasn't been issued, Justice Scalia.","start":3677.721,"stop":3680.033,"duration":2.31},{"text":"It's still pending.","start":3680.033,"stop":3680.751,"duration":0.72},{"text":"And that's what FERC has before it, and FERC has said that the CRA will not affect what license is issued, but I want to go back to a fundamental--","start":3680.751,"stop":3688.089,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you willing to concede that if whatever you ask for here affects that license, once its issued, that then Duke's intervention is proper?","start":3688.089,"stop":3697.32,"duration":9.23}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, because the United States can enter -- can affect the interests and represent the interests of its licensees.","start":3697.32,"stop":3704.756,"duration":7.44},{"text":"Duke's interest is completely derivative of the United States' power to confer a license on an energy producer.","start":3704.756,"stop":3711.673,"duration":6.92},{"text":"And the United States here is saying, no, they should not be allowed to intervene.","start":3711.673,"stop":3715.905,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought Duke said the problem is not the United States -- so much the United States granting a license.","start":3715.905,"stop":3721.839,"duration":5.93},{"text":"It's the license we requested was based upon a negotiated agreement among a number of entities, and that agreement goes out the window once -- on the basis of this lawsuit.","start":3721.839,"stop":3734.036,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"David C. Frederick","textObjs":[{"text":"The agreement is a private contract among various water users, and it is no different than the fact that all users of this river will be affected, one way or the other, by whatever decree this Court issues, whether they are on the South Carolina side or the North Carolina side.","start":3734.036,"stop":3749.576,"duration":15.54}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3749.576,"stop":3750.766,"duration":1.19},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3750.766,"stop":3751.718,"duration":0.95}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Oct 13, 2009","petitioner":"South Carolina","respondent":"North Carolina","docket":"138-orig","citation":"558US256(2010)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/558/256","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"Oct 1, 2007","decidedOn":"Jan 20, 2010"}